            <h2>Batangas City</h2>
            <h3>Industrial Port City of Calabarzon</h3>

            <img src="<?= $this->webroot ?>theme/weatherph/img/tourism/batangasCity1.png" alt="Batangas City">

            <p>Batangas City is discovered by Spanish missionaries in 1572. It was named Batangan due to numerous big logs or batang that abound the Calumpang River. Located 112 kilometers south of Manila, it has a total land area of 28,541 hectares divided into 105 barangays. It was proclaimed a City on July 23, 1969. From the day of its found- ing, the City has transformed from a budding city to a booming metropolis. It is now one of the major centers of commerce and industry south of Manila.</p>
            <p>The City’s international port, a vital link in the nautical highway, serves hundreds of thousands of passenger and tons of volume of domestic and foreign cargo.</p>
            <p>From a mere Php 40 million annual budget in 1988, the City has a current annual budget of Php 1.2 billion.</p>
            <p>Business and technology have drastically altered the City’s land- scape. Batangas City is the site of the biggest oil refineries in Asia, the Pilipinas Shell Petroleum Corporation, JG Summit Petro- chemical Corporation and the three natural gas combined cycle power plants – Sta. Rita, San Lorenzo of First Gas Power Plant Corporation, and Ilijan power plant of Korean Electric Company. This has a total generative capacity of 2,700 megawatts supply- ing 70% of the power requirements of the Luzon grid.</p>
            <p>Fueling the local economy are 47 banking institutions, three public markets, and 3,000 small and medium business establish- ments.</p>
            <p>Although the City has been identified as an industrializing city, the emphasis on agriculture production goes hand in hand with industrialization to realize its growth targets. The City produces 75% of livestock that is supplied to Manila and 25% for local consumption.</p>
            <p>Education is also an equal priority. The City government runs 116 daycare centers and one tertiary school. Environmental protection is another priority program in the City. The passage of the Batangas City Environment Code and the establishment of a Materials Recovery Facility in every barangay to sustain the ecological management of solid wastes is a reiteration of the City’s assertive campaign to make cleaning and waste segregation as a way of life. This is Batangas City today, a fast urbanizing city in harmony with ecological balance.</p>

